3. MATHEMATICAL MODEL ‚Äî MEMORY AS STRUCTURE, NOT STORAGE

Let a memory be represented not as a vector v \in \mathbb{R}^{n},
but as a graph of constraints:

M = (S, R, I)

Where:
	‚Ä¢	S = symbols (nodes)
	‚Ä¢	R = relationships (edges)
	‚Ä¢	I = invariants (constraints)

This is a symbolic manifold, not a numeric vector.

Memory is preserved when:

I(S, R) = \text{constant}

A memory retrieval event becomes:

\operatorname{Reconstruct}(M) = \operatorname{Solve}(I)

Meaning:

Memory is reconstructed by solving constraints, not retrieving content.

This is the key insight.

Symbolic memory = procedural reconstruction, not passive recall.

